Let&#39;s do that together.
`vector&lt;int&gt; v;`
vector is a wrapper of pure array allocated with a new operator, so its elements can be accessed by applying pointer arithmetic.
`v[i], *(v.begin() +i)` access to i-th element. Indexing from 0.
How to iterate
```
for(int i = 0; i &lt; v.size; i++) cout &lt;&lt; v[i] &lt;&lt; endl;
for(int x: v) cout &lt;&lt; v[i] &lt;&lt; endl;
for(auto it = v.begin(); it != v.end(); ++it) cout &lt;&lt; v[i] &lt;&lt; endl;
```
Let&#39;s take another example
`map&lt;int, list&lt;int&gt; &gt; mp;`
It&#39;s not a linear data structure, rather a tree one.
But iteration is similar.
`for(auto node: mp)` where node is `std:: pair&lt;int, list&lt;int&gt;&gt;`
Inside this for loop you can get the `list&lt;int&gt;` with the expression `node.second` and iterate through it in a similar way.

```
for(auto node: mp)// node is pair&lt;int, list&lt;int&gt; &gt;
{  int key = node.first;
   cout &lt;&lt; key &lt;&lt; &quot; &quot;;
   for(auto elem: node.second) // elem is int
      cout &lt;&lt; elem &lt;&lt; &quot; &quot;;
   cout &lt;&lt; endl;
}
```

